<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Camera Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Create cinematic camera sequences, conversation shots, fixed-camera moments, security camera-style movement, and camera-controlled mission scenes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Camera Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Camera Event Points are one of the most important mission scripting tools in the Mission
        Editor. They can be used to create cinematic effects, conversation cutscenes, security camera
        style views, fixed-camera moments, scripted camera movement, and mission scenes where the
        camera temporarily leaves normal gameplay control.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A camera sequence is usually made from a small group of related Event Points:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create Camera</Bold> — starts the camera sequence and defines the shot type, speed, delay, and camera flags.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Camera Waypoints</Bold> — optional intermediate positions the camera can travel through.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create Target</Bold> — the required end/target of the camera sequence. The camera always faces the target.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_eventpoints_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical structure:</Run>
                <Run> Camera sequences need a Start and an End. The Start is Create Camera. The End is Create Target. Camera Waypoints are optional intermediate points between them.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Camera Sequence Structure
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A basic camera sequence starts at the <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point and ends at the
        <Bold>Create Target</Bold> Event Point. Optional <Bold>Camera Waypoints</Bold> can be added
        between them to control the path the camera takes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">Create Camera  ->  Camera Waypoint(s)  ->  Create Target</TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Camera Waypoints are not mandatory. A simple camera sequence can go directly from Create
        Camera to Create Target. However, waypoints are useful when you want the camera to move
        through specific positions before arriving at the target.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The camera will always face the target. This affects how the shot looks and how the camera
        travels. When placing waypoints, always think about both the camera position and the target
        position. The camera’s path may not look the way you expect if the target is in the wrong place.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Camera facing rule:</Run>
                <Run> When the camera spawns, it always faces the target. Place the Create Target Event Point where the camera should look.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_sequence_diagram.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Camera Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point starts the camera sequence. This is the Event
        Point that should be placed behind the trigger that begins the camera event.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, if a camera sequence should play when an NPC is arrested, the
        <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point should be triggered by that arrest condition.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_create_camera_overview.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Adding a Create Camera Event Point</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select <Bold>Create Camera</Bold>, and
        click <Bold>OK</Bold>. The Edit EventPoint window opens with the common properties and the
        Create Camera-specific settings.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_add_create_camera.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Camera Type</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>The <Bold>Camera Type</Bold> controls the style of camera shot used when the sequence runs.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_type_dropdown.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Normal</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The most commonly used camera type. This is the letterboxed camera style with black bars at the top and bottom. It is commonly used for conversation cutscenes and cinematic mission moments.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Security Cam</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Uses the regular player camera style and can move to Camera Waypoints before snapping back behind the player. This is useful for fixed camera or security-camera effects.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Camcorder</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to behave similarly to Normal. It may be a legacy or unused variation.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">News</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to behave similarly to Normal. It may be a legacy or unused variation.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Targeting</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">No obvious effect has been observed. Treat this as uncertain unless deliberately testing it.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8"><Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12"><TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0"><Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical recommendation:</Run><Run> Existing missions primarily use Normal and Security Cam. For most new camera sequences, start with Normal unless you specifically need a security-camera style effect.</Run></TextBlock></Border></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Speed and Delay</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Create Camera has two important motion timing properties: <Bold>Speed</Bold> and <Bold>Delay</Bold>.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_speed_delay.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Speed</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls how fast the camera moves between waypoints and toward the target. A typical value is around <Bold>50</Bold>, but it can be adjusted higher or lower depending on the desired camera movement.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Delay</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls how many frames the camera waits before it begins moving toward its waypoints or target. Use this if you want the shot to hold before movement begins.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Create Camera Flags</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Create Camera has flags that alter how the camera sequence behaves.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_flags.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Pause Player</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Prevents the player from moving while the camera event is active. This is important for conversation cutscenes or cinematic sequences where the player should not run away.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Direction Lock</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to lock the camera to the direction the waypoint or camera path is facing. The exact behaviour should be tested for the specific sequence.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Cannot Be Skipped</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Prevents the player from skipping through the cutscene. Use this when the camera event is important for mission logic, dialogue, or player instruction.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Triggering the Camera Sequence</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>The <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point is the important trigger point for the camera sequence. This is what starts the camera event.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">Put Create Camera behind the trigger that should start the camera sequence. Examples include:</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> — the camera starts when the player enters an area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Person Arrested</Bold> — the camera starts when a specific NPC is arrested.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Killed or Arrested</Bold> — the camera starts when a target is neutralised.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Finished</Bold> — the camera starts after dialogue ends.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> — the camera starts after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Switch</Bold> — the camera starts after an object or switch is used.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8"><Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14"><TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15"><Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical trigger detail:</Run><Run> Trigger the Create Camera Event Point. Do not rely on the waypoint or target to start the sequence. Create Camera is the start of the camera event.</Run></TextBlock></Border></BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">Camera Waypoints</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph><Bold>Camera Waypoint</Bold> Event Points are optional intermediate camera positions. They let you control the route the camera travels before it reaches the target.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">Each waypoint can be placed at an arbitrary X/Z position and Y height. This allows the camera to move through the world, rise, drop, sweep across an area, move around a character, or travel toward the final shot.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_waypoints_overview.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Placing Camera Waypoints</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Place Camera Waypoints between the Create Camera start position and the Create Target end point. The camera will visit these waypoints before reaching the target.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">Use the position values to place the waypoint in world space. The Y value is especially important for camera work because it controls camera height.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_waypoint_position.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Waypoint Speed, Delay, and Flags</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Camera Waypoints expose similar properties to Create Camera, such as speed, delay, and flags. In practice, these are usually inherited from the Create Camera Event Point, and changing them on individual waypoints appears to have no obvious effect.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">For predictable results, configure the main camera behaviour on the <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point and use Camera Waypoints primarily for position/path control.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8"><Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12"><TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF"><Run FontWeight="Bold">Waypoint rule of thumb:</Run><Run> Use waypoints to control where the camera travels. Use Create Camera to control the shot type, trigger, speed, delay, and important camera flags.</Run></TextBlock></Border></BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">Create Target Event Point</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>The <Bold>Create Target</Bold> Event Point is the end or target of the camera sequence. The camera looks toward this target when the camera sequence is active.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">A camera sequence must have both a <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> start and a <Bold>Create Target</Bold> end. Without a proper target, the camera sequence may not look where intended.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_create_target_overview.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Target Type</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Create Target has an extra <Bold>Target Type</Bold> parameter.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8"><Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_camera_target_type.png" MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Normal</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The camera target is the Event Point’s position or target waypoint path. This is the normal fixed target mode.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Attached</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Uses an attached or relative mode handled by the camera system. The original editor exposes no separate attached Event Point field, so the exact link behaviour is limited by the camera system.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Nearest Living Thing</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The target dynamically resolves to the nearest living actor rather than a fixed waypoint position.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Zoom and Rotate Camera</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>Create Target also exposes <Bold>Zoom</Bold> and <Bold>Rotate Camera</Bold> options.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Zoom</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to represent the camera zoom level, but no obvious effect has been observed in current testing.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Rotate Camera</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to suggest that the camera can rotate, but no obvious effect has been observed in current testing.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8"><Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12"><TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF"><Run FontWeight="Bold">Target placement tip:</Run><Run> Place the target where the camera should look, not necessarily where the camera should travel. The camera position and the target position are different concepts.</Run></TextBlock></Border></BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">Practical Camera Examples</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Conversation Cutscene</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Use <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> with camera type <Bold>Normal</Bold>. Place the camera where the shot should begin, add optional Camera Waypoints if the camera should move, and place <Bold>Create Target</Bold> near the speaker or focus of the conversation. Enable <Bold>Pause Player</Bold> if the player should not move during the scene.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Security Camera-Style Area View</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Use <Bold>Security Cam</Bold> when the player enters a radius or area. The camera can move to waypoints and then return to normal gameplay view.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Objective Reveal</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Trigger Create Camera after an objective is completed, then move the camera through waypoints toward a target object, door, enemy, or escape route. Use this to show the player where to go next.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Arrest or Enemy Defeat Cutaway</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Place Create Camera behind a <Bold>Person Arrested</Bold>, <Bold>Killed or Arrested</Bold>, or similar trigger. The camera sequence can then show the target, a door opening, a reward location, or a new threat.</Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">Basic Camera Sequence Workflow</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what should trigger the camera sequence.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Create Camera</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the camera type, usually <Bold>Normal</Bold> or <Bold>Security Cam</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Create Camera trigger. This is what starts the whole camera sequence.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Speed</Bold>, usually around <Bold>50</Bold> as a starting value.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Delay</Bold> if the camera should wait before moving.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set flags such as <Bold>Pause Player</Bold> or <Bold>Cannot Be Skipped</Bold> if needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add optional <Bold>Camera Waypoints</Bold> if the camera should travel through intermediate positions.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place each waypoint at the correct X/Z position and Y height.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Create Target</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the target where the camera should look.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the Target Type, usually <Bold>Normal</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the sequence in game.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the camera looks wrong, adjust the target position first, because the camera always faces the target.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8"><Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14"><TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15"><Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run><Run> Create Camera exists, Create Target exists, Create Camera has the correct trigger, any waypoints are positioned correctly, and the target is where the camera should look.</Run></TextBlock></Border></BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>